    <node id="EGFR" name="Epidermal growth factor receptor" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(EGF | (FAK_SRC:2 &amp; ITG_AB) | TGFBR) &amp; !RPTP"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P00533"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Epidermal growth factor receptor
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P00533

Receptor tyrosine kinase binding ligands of the EGF family


0 = inactive
1 = active, ligand binding dimer formation and autophosphorylation"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1060" y="456" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="HGFR" name="Hepatocyte growth factor receptor" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(HGF | ITG_AB) &amp; !RPTP"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P08581"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Hepatocyte growth factor receptor
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P08581

Receptor tyrosine kinase that transduces signals from the extracellular matrix into the cytoplasm by binding to hepatocyte growth factor/HGF ligand

0 = inactive
1 = active, ligand binding dimer formation and autophosphorylation"

</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1531" y="382" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="ITG_AB" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="ECM &amp; RAP1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <comment>"Integrins are transmembrane receptors composed of 2 subunit (alpha and beta) capable of interact and adhere to the ECM. the combination of the different alpha and beta subunits specify the type of ligand (e.g. fibronectin, vitronectin, collagen and laminin.).

0 = normal integrin binding to the ECM
1 = high affinity binding to the ECM, increased avidity for ligand (RAP1 =1)"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1302" y="382" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="FAK_SRC" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="(ROS &amp; ITG_AB) | (ITG_AB &amp; HGFR &amp; EGFR)"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(ROS &amp; !ITG_AB) | ((EGFR | HGFR) &amp; !ITG_AB) | (ITG_AB &amp; !(ROS | (EGFR &amp; HGFR)))"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:Q05397"/>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P12931"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Focal adhesion kinase 1
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q05397

Phosphorylated on tyrosine residues upon activation, e.g. upon integrin signaling. Tyr-397 is the major autophosphorylation site, but other kinases can also phosphorylate this residue. Phosphorylation at Tyr-397 promotes interaction with SRC and SRC family members, leading to phosphorylation at Tyr-576, Tyr-577 and at additional tyrosine residues.


Proto-oncogene tyrosine-protein kinase Src
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P12931

Normally maintained in an inactive conformation with the SH2 domain engaged with Tyr-530, the SH3 domain engaged with the SH2-kinase linker, and Tyr-419 dephosphorylated. Interaction with FAK lead to the rupture of this intramolecular link and to the formation of a complex kinase.

0 = inactive
1 = partial activation of the 2 kinases and formation of the FAK &amp; SRC complex kinase
2 = full activation of the 2 kinases and formation of the FAK &amp; SRC complex kinase"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1459" y="521" style="Multivalued"/>
    </node>
    <node id="RAS" name="RAS" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="EGFR | FAK_SRC | JAK | HGFR | TGFBR"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P01112"/>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P01116"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"GTPase HRas
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P01112
GTPase KRas
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P01116


Involved in the activation of Ras protein signal transduction. Alternates between an inactive form bound to GDP and an active form bound to GTP.


0 = inactive, GDP-binding
1 = active, GTP-binding"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1062" y="545" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="RAF1" name="RAF proto-oncogene serine/threonine-protein kinase" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="RAS"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P04049"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"RAF proto-oncogene serine/threonine-protein kinase
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P04049

Serine/threonine-protein kinase that acts as a regulatory link between the membrane-associated Ras GTPases and the MAPK/ERK cascade

0 = inactive
1 = phosphorylated, kinase domain active"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1064" y="630" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="MEK" name="Dual specificity mitogen-activated protein kinase kinase 1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="RAF1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:Q02750"/>
          <link xlink:href=""/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Dual specificity mitogen-activated protein kinase kinase 1
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q02750

Dual specificity protein kinase which acts as an essential component of the MAP kinase signal transduction pathway. Binding of extracellular ligands such as growth factors, cytokines and hormones to their cell-surface receptors activates RAS and this initiates RAF1 activation. RAF1 then further activates the dual-specificity protein kinases MAP2K1/MEK1 and MAP2K2/MEK2


0 = inactive
1 = phosphorylated, kinase domain active"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1065" y="720" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="ERK" name="Mitogen-activated protein kinase 3/1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="MEK"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P27361"/>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P28482"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Mitogen-activated protein kinase 3/1 (ERK1/ERK2)
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P27361
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P28482

Serine/threonine kinase which acts as an essential component of the MAP kinase signal transduction pathway. MAPK1/ERK2 and MAPK3/ERK1 are the 2 MAPKs which play an important role in the MAPK/ERK cascade. Phosphorylated by MAP2K1/MEK1 and MAP2K2/MEK2 on Thr-202 and Tyr-204 in response to external stimuli


0 = inactive
1 = phosphorylated, kinase domain active"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1067" y="812" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="PI3K" name="Phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="RAS | FAK_SRC"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P42336"/>
          <link xlink:href=""/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Phosphatidylinositol 4,5-bisphosphate 3-kinase catalytic subunit alpha isoform
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P42336

Phosphoinositide-3-kinase (PI3K) that phosphorylates PtdIns (Phosphatidylinositol), PtdIns4P (Phosphatidylinositol 4-phosphate) and PtdIns(4,5)P2 (Phosphatidylinositol 4,5-bisphosphate) to generate phosphatidylinositol 3,4,5-trisphosphate (PIP3)

0 = inactive
1 = kinase active, generates PIP3"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1190" y="625" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="ILK" name="Integrin-linked protein kinase" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="ITG_AB &amp; PI3K"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:Q13418"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Integrin-linked protein kinase
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q13418

Receptor-proximal protein kinase regulating integrin-mediated signal transduction.

0 = inactive
1 = kinase active"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1240" y="708" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="AKT" name="RAC-alpha serine/threonine-protein kinase" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="PI3K &amp; ILK"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P31749"/>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P31751"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"RAC-alpha serine/threonine-protein kinase (AKT1)
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P31749
RAC-beta serine/threonine-protein kinase (AKT2)
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P31751


AKT1/2 are 2 of 3 closely related serine/threonine-protein kinases (AKT1, AKT2 and AKT3) called the AKT kinase, and which regulate many processes including metabolism, proliferation, cell survival, growth and angiogenesis.Three specific sites, one in the kinase domain (Thr-308) and the two other ones in the C-terminal regulatory region (Ser-473 and Tyr-474), need to be phosphorylated for its full activation.


0 = inactive
1 = phosphorylated, kinase domain active"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1184" y="787" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="GSK3B" name="Glycogen synthase kinase-3 beta" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!AKT &amp; !ERK &amp; !DVL"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P49841"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Glycogen synthase kinase-3 beta
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P49841

Constitutively active protein kinase that acts as a negative regulator in the hormonal control of glucose homeostasis, Wnt signaling and regulation of transcription factors and microtubules, by phosphorylating and inactivating glycogen synthase (GYS1 or GYS2), EIF2B, CTNNB1/beta-catenin, APC, AXIN1, DPYSL2/CRMP2, JUN, NFATC1/NFATC, MAPT/TAU and MACF1


0 = inactive
1 = active kinase "
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1591" y="592" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="DVL" name="Segment polarity protein dishevelled homolog 2" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="CK1 &amp; YAP_TAZ"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:O14641"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Segment polarity protein dishevelled homolog 2
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/O14641

Plays a role in the signal transduction pathways mediated by multiple Wnt genes. Participates both in canonical and non-canonical Wnt signaling by binding to the cytoplasmic C-terminus of frizzled family members and transducing the Wnt signal to down-stream effectors.

0 = inactive
1 = active, phosphorylated"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1667" y="341" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="CK1" name="Casein kinase I isoform epsilon" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="WNT"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P49674"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Casein kinase I isoform epsilon
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P49674

Casein kinases are operationally defined by their preferential utilization of acidic proteins such as caseins as substrates. Can phosphorylate a large number of proteins. Participates in Wnt signaling. Phosphorylates DVL1 and DVL2.

0 = inactive
1 = kinase active, removal of inhibitory phoshatase"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="2221" y="343" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="FAT4" name="Protocadherin Fat 4" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="FAT4_L &amp; !ERK"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:Q6V0I7"/>
          <link xlink:href=""/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Protocadherin Fat 4
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q6V0I7

FAT4 plays a role in the maintenance of planar cell polarity as well as in inhibition of YAP1-mediated neuroprogenitor cell proliferation and differentiation.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="939" y="624" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="LATS" name="Serine/threonine-protein kinase LATS1/2" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(FAT4 | (ECad_AJ &amp; BCat_AJ)) &amp; !PI3K"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:O95835"/>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:Q9NRM7"/>
          <link xlink:href=""/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Serine/threonine-protein kinase LATS1
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/O95835
Serine/threonine-protein kinase LATS2
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q9NRM7

Negative regulator of YAP1 in the Hippo signaling pathway. Phosphorylation of YAP1 by LATS1/2 inhibits its translocation into the nucleus to regulate cellular genes important for cell proliferation, cell death, and cell migration

0 = inactive
1 = phosphorylated active"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="941" y="762" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="NOTCH" name="Neurogenic locus notch homolog protein 1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="DELTA"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P46531"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Neurogenic locus notch homolog protein 1
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P46531

Functions as a receptor for membrane-bound ligands Jagged1, Jagged2 and Delta1 to regulate cell-fate determination. Upon ligand activation through the released notch intracellular domain (NICD) it forms a transcriptional activator complex.

0 = inactive
1 = active, delta ligand binding"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="660" y="451" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="YAP_TAZ" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!LATS"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:P46937"/>
          <link xlink:href="uniprot:Q9GZV5"/>
          <link xlink:href=""/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Transcriptional coactivator YAP1
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P46937
WW domain-containing transcription regulator protein 1
http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q9GZV5

Transcriptional regulator which can act both as a coactivator and a corepressor and is the critical downstream regulatory target in the Hippo signaling pathway. Phosphorylation of YAP1 by LATS1/2 inhibits its translocation into the nucleus to regulate cellular genes important for cell proliferation, cell death, and cell migration.


0 = localized @ cytoplasm
1 = localized  @  nucleus





"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="913" y="919" style=""/>
    </node>
