      </value>
      <annotation>
        <comment>"Mesenchymal phenotype output. Focal Adhesion formation between Cell and ECM

0 = lack of migratory capacity
1 = ability to migrate over the ECM by formation of Focal Adhesion complexes"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="987" y="1285" style="Mesenchymal marker multi-valued"/>
    </node>
    <edge id="FAT4:LATS" from="FAT4" to="LATS" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:17045801"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:19048595"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"In Drosophila that FAT cadherin modulate the Salvador/Warts/Hippo Signaling Pathway (Bennet et al. 2006).
(Qi et al. 2009) showed in mice NOG8 cells  that loss of FAT4 expression distrupts Hippo pathway leading to an abnormal activation of  YAP activity."
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="RAF1:MEK" from="RAF1" to="MEK" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:8019005"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Raf can phosphorylate and activate MEK (Gardner et al 1994).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="FAK_SRC:RAP1" from="FAK_SRC" to="RAP1" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:9032297"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:11604500"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:8070403"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:8524240"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:19208836"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"The integrin adhesion generates the formation of  a complex between FAK_SRC and p130CAS, the latter being a substrate for SRC phosphorylation (Schlaepfer et al. 1997, Russel et al. 2001). The phosphorylated p130CAS then recruits Crk (Sakai et al. 1994) which work as adapter for the GEF protein C3G that is an activator of RAP1 (Gotoh et al. 1995). 
(Ricono et al. 2009) also pointed to a cascade of phosphorylation composed by: SRC_FAK--&gt;p130CAS--&gt;CrkII/C3G--&gt;RAP1. Using FG human pancreatic carcinoma cells, show that cells adhesion to anti-β1 led to a Rac1 and Rap1 activity independent of EGF."
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1520,630" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="FAK_SRC:ECad_AJ" from="FAK_SRC" to="ECad_AJ" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:11836526"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>In HEK293 cells, E-cadherin ubiquitination was increased by temperature shift. In particular in the presence of v-SRC, E-cadherin was tyrosine phosphorylated and Hakai (ubiquitin like protein) was effectively co-immunoprecipitated with E-cadherin (Fujita et al. 2002).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1575,568 1575,750 2057,754" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="FAK_SRC:BCat_AJ" from="FAK_SRC" to="BCat_AJ" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:16651417"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:10593980"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Koenig et al. 2006) showed that in Panc-1 cells upon Collagen I there is an activation of FAK_SRC with an increased phosphorylation of β-catenin and its localization to the nucleus. Other evidences support how SRC is also involved into β-catenin phosphorylation in this case in vitro and reducing the binding affinity between β-catenin and E-cadherin (Roura et al. 1999), in particular Tyr654
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1870,542 1986,542" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="FAK_SRC:RPTP" from="FAK_SRC" to="RPTP" minvalue="2" sign="negative">
      <edgevisualsetting points="1900,534" anchor="NE" style="Predicted"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="FAK_SRC:EGFR" from="FAK_SRC" to="EGFR" minvalue="2" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:11756413"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Moro et al. 2002) reported how NIH3T3 cells expressing human EGFR and plated on fibronectin showed a coimmunoprecipitation of β1 and EGFR. Furthermore, ECV304 and human primary skin fibroblast adherent on matrix proteins stimulated EGFR phosphorylation and association with the β1 integrin. SRC is phosphorylated on Tyr416 when ECV304 cells are plated on integrin ligands indicating that integrin mediated adhesion induces SRC kinase activation. Under PP1 treatment (a SRC inhibitor) there is no more complex formation between αvβ3 and EGFR similarly if it is expressed a kinase negative form of SRC the complex formation is strongly reduced.
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1475,479" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="FAK_SRC:RAS" from="FAK_SRC" to="RAS" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15077193"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:7997267"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Hecker et al. 2004) it is shown how in U251MG cells FAK generates an indirect induction of RAS by sequestering p120GAP (an inhibitor of RAS). (Schlaepfer et al. 1994) for NIH3T3 murine fibroblast the SRC-mediated phosphorylation of FAK-Tyr925 create a docking site for GRB2, thus linking RAS to integrin signaling.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1217,567" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="FAK_SRC:PI3K" from="FAK_SRC" to="PI3K" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15166238"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>FAK activates PI3K in human lung fibrobast (Xia et al. 2004)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1235,580" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="FAK_SRC:STAT3" from="FAK_SRC" to="STAT3" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:9566874"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Turkson et al. 1998) in NIH/3T3 transfected with v-SRC and a luciferase reporter induced by STAT3, showed that an increase in STAT3 activity in a dose dependent fashion from SRC. It could be abrogated with inactive STAT3 expression.
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="699,529 631,778" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="FAK_SRC:PAK" from="FAK_SRC" to="PAK" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:9032297"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:11604500"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:8070403"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:9808620"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:8107774"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"The integrin adhesion generates the formation of  a complex between FAK_SRC and p130CAS, the latter being a substrate for SRC phosphorylation (Schlaepfer et al. 1997, Russel et al. 2001). The phosphorylated p130CAS then recruits Crk (Sakai et al. 1994) which work as adapter for the DOCK180 protein that is an activator of RAC1 (Kiyokawa et al. 1998). RAC1 then regulates PAK1 (Manser et al. 1994)
"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1463,588 1407,654" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="FAK_SRC:FA" from="FAK_SRC" to="FA" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <edgevisualsetting points="1481,590 1460,736 1461,1329" anchor="NE" style="Modeling activation"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="FAK_SRC:JNK" from="FAK_SRC" to="JNK" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:10766791"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Yoshizumi et al. 2000) showed in fibroblast and vascular smooth muscle cells that SRC is the main regulator of ROS-mediated JNK activation via p130CAS dependent mechanism. A knock-out of SRC or its inhibition by PP2 results in a blockade of the ROS dependent JNK activation
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1471,588 1453,675 1440,744 1439,1077 1401,1077" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="LATS:YAP_TAZ" from="LATS" to="YAP_TAZ" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:18158288"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>YAP is a substrate of LATS kinase, phosphorylation of YAP by LATS inhibits its translocation to the nucleus which lead to sequestration of the YAP in the cytoplasm (Hao et al. 2008).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="953,816" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="RPTP_L:RPTP" from="RPTP_L" to="RPTP" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:8264577"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Receptor tyrosine phosphatases (R-PTPases) feature PTPase domains in the context of a receptor-like transmembrane topology (Sap et al. 1994)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="RAP1:ITG_AB" from="RAP1" to="ITG_AB" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:12546659"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:10688643"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Bos et al 2003) reported that  RAP1 regulates the inside-out activation of most integrins by mediating their polarized spatial redistribution and stabilization in an active conformation. Jurkat cells, the introduction of Rap1 induces integrin αLβ2 (LFA1)-mediated adhesion to ICAMs that was inhibited by the introduction of an interfering mutant of Rap1 (Katagiri et al 2000)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1500,637 1353,638" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="RAP1:p120_AJ" from="RAP1" to="p120_AJ" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15857834"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Rap1 effector AF6 associates with p120-catenin and this binding increases the interaction of p120-catenin with E-cadheri (Hoshino et al. 2005)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1535,632 1558,632 1557,501" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="GSK3B:BCat" from="GSK3B" to="BCat" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:23169527"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>GSK3β together with CK1α, APC and Axin form a destruction complex that phosphorylates β-catenin and triggers its ubiquitination and proteasomal degradation resulting in a low level of cytoplasmic β-catenin (Stamos et al. 2013).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1657,614" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="GSK3B:SNAIL" from="GSK3B" to="SNAIL" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15448698"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>GSK3β regulates SNAIL by phosphorilation:  degradation or increasing its nuclear export (Zhou et al. 2004).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1651,860" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="GSK3B:SLUG" from="GSK3B" to="SLUG" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:23851495"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>GSK3β-mediated phosphorylation of SLUG facilitates the protein turnover (Kao et al. 2014).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1640,657 1639,823 1528,822" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="JNK:SNAIL" from="JNK" to="SNAIL" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:23557251"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Zhan et al. 2013) showed that interfering with JNK or c-Jun can dowregulate SNAIL (AP1 is dowtream of c-Jun and upregulate SNAIL).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1630,1141" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="JNK:BCat_AJ" from="JNK" to="BCat_AJ" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:19667122"/>
          <link xlink:href=""/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>JNK phosphorylates β-catenin and disrupt its localization with E-cadherin at the cell membrane. The experiments were performed on keratinocytes, A431 and MDCK epithelial cells and on HEK293T (M.-H. Lee et al. 2009).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1413,1280 1976,1280 1971,627 2061,626" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="NFkB:SNAIL" from="NFkB" to="SNAIL" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15286702"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>p65 subunit can induce SNAIL transcriptional activity (Barberà et al. 2004) 
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1275,1089 1612,1090" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="NFkB:HIF1a" from="NFkB" to="HIF1a" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:18393939"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(van Uden, Kenneth, and Rocha 2008) showed that NF-κB different units bind to HIF1-α promoter
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1037,1144" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="SLUG:ECad" from="SLUG" to="ECad" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:12508111"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Bolós et al. 2003b) SLUG is a transcriptional repressor of E-cadherin
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1833,866" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="SLUG:ZEB" from="SLUG" to="ZEB" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:21593765"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Wels et al. 2011) showed that SLUG induce ZEB1 transcriptional activity in keratinocytes.
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1547,880 1742,881" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ECad:ECad_AJ" from="ECad" to="ECad_AJ" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <comment>Modeling interaction, maturation of the mRNA and translocation of the protein to the membrane
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1903,709" anchor="NE" style="Modeling activation"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ECad:AJ" from="ECad" to="AJ" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <edgevisualsetting points="1886,716 1886,1306" anchor="NE" style="Modeling activation"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="MEK:ERK" from="MEK" to="ERK" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:1321146"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>MEKs act as dual specificity kinases and phosphorylate the regulatory Tyr and Thr residues of ERK activating it (Seger et al. 1992)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1097,784" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="HGF:HGFR" from="HGF" to="HGFR" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:1846706"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Bottaro et al. 1991) identified the oncogene cMET as the receptor of HGF in human mammary gland cells B5/589 treated with HGF 
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ECM:ITG_AB" from="ECM" to="ITG_AB" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:﻿16169468"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Paszek et al. 2005), hypothesize and that tissue stiffness could promote malignant behaviour by modulating integrins.

non-malignant MCF10A growing on normal mammary ECM (170 Pa) formed small growth-arrested and polarized acini with adherens junction and a central lumen. MCF10A could phosphorylate FAK on pY397 only on rigid ECM and thus recruit vinculin to the integrins. MCF10A within 12h of plating were more capable of migrating on the stiff versus non-stiff ECM.
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="PI3K:AKT" from="PI3K" to="AKT" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:9005852"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:9094314"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Akt activity correlates with the amount of phosphatidylinositol-3,4-bisphosphate (PtdIns-3,4-P2) in vivo (Franke et al. 1997).
(Dario R. Alessi et al. 1997) showed that PDK1 uses PIP3 as a substrate to phosphorylate AKT increasing its activity."
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1217,717" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="PI3K:ILK" from="PI3K" to="ILK" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:9736715"/>
          <link xlink:href=""/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Delcommenne et al. 1998) showed that in rat intestinal epithelial cells IEC18 treated with insulin there was a rapid activation of ILK that was promptly inhibited by the addition of wormannin or Ly294002 (two PI3K inhibitors).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1284,673" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="PI3K:LATS" from="PI3K" to="LATS" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:23359693"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Fan, Kim, and Gumbiner 2013) showed that PI3K inhibits LATS activity by recruiting PDK1 and thus destructing the complex that activate LATS. This has been proven in epithelial cells like MCF10A, MCF7, A431
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1197,704 1000,704" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="PI3K:PAK" from="PI3K" to="PAK" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:10995762"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(King et al. 2000) showed that PAK1 is phosphorylated and activated by the PIP3 dependent kinase PDK1 and thus directly related to PI3K activity.
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1394,654" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="HGFR:FAK_SRC" from="HGFR" to="FAK_SRC" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:21119598"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>HeyA8  cells plated on fibronectin show FAK activation (p-FAK Y397) and MET activation. This double activation can be reduced by either targeting α5 with an antibody or MET with siRNA. The same cell line HeyA8 were plated on fibronectin and then treated with α5 antibody and different doses of HGF. Resulting in activation of SRC (Tyr416) and an increase in activation of FAK (Mitra et al. 2011).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1546,450 1525,490" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="HGFR:RAS" from="HGFR" to="RAS" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15077193"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:7997267"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"(Hecker et al. 2004) showed in U251MG cells that FAK generates an indirect induction of RAS by sequestering p120GAP (an inhibitor of RAS).
(Schlaepfer et al. 1994) in NIH3T3 showed that SRC-mediated phosphorylation of FAK-Tyr925 create a docking site for GRB2."
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1574,469 1425,469 1425,549" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="HGFR:BCat" from="HGFR" to="BCat" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:10425198"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15226396"/>
          <link xlink:href=""/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>C-MET can form complexes with β-catenin and upon activation release the catenin in the cytoplasm (Hiscox and Jiang 1999). As a matter of fact c-MET coimmunoprecipitation with β-catenin can be inhibited in a dose dependent manner with HGF (G. Xu et al. 2004)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1760,416" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="TCF_LEF:SLUG" from="TCF_LEF" to="SLUG" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:14623871"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Conacci-Sorrell et al. 2003) reports how SLUG but not SNAIL promoter is activated by β-catenin TCF_LEF signaling in HEK293T cells
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1636,851" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="TCF_LEF:SNAIL" from="TCF_LEF" to="SNAIL" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:20372961"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:21633953"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>TCF_LEF--»miR30--|SNAIL, (Liao et al 2010 and Kumarswamy et al 2012)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1758,1014" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="EGF:EGFR" from="EGF" to="EGFR" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:12954170"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:7680558"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>EGFR from A431 after the administration of soluble EGF,  is usually autophosphorylated at multiple tyrosine (Tyr) residues, which among others include Tyr992, Tyr1068, Tyr1086, Tyr1148, and Tyr1173 (Guo et al. 2003) . Some of these residues as Tyr992 harbour SH2 binding sites (Sierke, Longo, and Koland 1993).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ILK:AKT" from="ILK" to="AKT" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:22310280"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"(Serrano et al. 2013), reported that epithelial cells incubated with TGFβ1 showed an increased phosphorylation of AKT on Ser 473 (one of the activation sites of AKT). Addition of QLT0267 (ILK inhibitor) reduced Ser473 phosphorylation to control levels.
"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1245,746 1229,746" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="HIF1a:SNAIL" from="HIF1a" to="SNAIL" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:18427106"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>HIF1-α induces the transcription of LOX, this protein binds SNAIL protecting it from GSK3β phosphorylation and thus from degradation, thus having a stabilizing effect (Sahlgren et al. 2008). 
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1107,1066" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="HIF1a:SLUG" from="HIF1a" to="SLUG" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:20509143"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Storci et al. 2010) showed in MCF7 that NF-κB enhanced the formation of mammosphere and that this was inhibited by inactive SLUG. Corroborating previous results that showed how SLUG was upregulated by HIF1-α under hypoxic conditions (HIF1-α is a well known downstream target of NF-κB)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1202,1086 1204,860" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="TGFBR:SMAD" from="TGFBR" to="SMAD" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:9759503"/>
          <link xlink:href=""/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>TGFB-RI phosphorylates Smad2 and Smad3, triggering oligomerization of Smad2 or Smad3 with Smad4. The activated Smad heterooligomers move to the nucleus where they regulate gene expression (Massague 1998).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="TGFBR:RAS" from="TGFBR" to="RAS" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:17673906"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>TGFB-R I/II complex is able to phosphorylate ShcA, this induces it association with Grb2/Sos thus initiating the MAP ERK pathway of phosphorylation which in its canonical pattern has as first step the activation of RAS by the ShcA/Grb2/Sos complex (M. K. Lee et al. 2007) .
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="860,586" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="TGFBR:JNK" from="TGFBR" to="JNK" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:19114990"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>TGFB receptors interact with TRAF6 and induce the formation of K63-linked poly-ubiquitin chains on TRAF6. Poly-ubiquitinated TRAF6 recruits TAK1 to activate JNK/p38 (Zhang 2009).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="897,483 893,1225 1383,1222" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="TGFBR:NFkB" from="TGFBR" to="NFkB" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:23858099"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:20200282"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>NF-kB is under the control of TGFB along the signaling pathway TAK1/IKK/NF-kB . this comes directly from the fact that IKK is known to be regulated by TAK1 (TGFB activated kinase 1) by phosphorylation (Ataie-Kachoie et al. 2013; Ear et al. 2010).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="778,480 780,1198 1246,1195" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="TGFBR:EGFR" from="TGFBR" to="EGFR" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:19147560"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>TGFBR induces TNF-a-converting enzyme (TACE) to release TNF-a (shedding) which binds to EGFR (S. E. Wang et al. 2009).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="964,467" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="AKT:GSK3B" from="AKT" to="GSK3B" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15448698"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Treatment with IGF or EGF  (of MCF7-Snail cells and HEK293-Snail cells) lead to AKT activation, thus GSK3B inactivation (Zhou et al. 2004).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1258,801 1621,803" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="AKT:NFkB" from="AKT" to="NFkB" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:19609947"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>AKT regulates the transcriptional activity of (NF-κB) by inducing the degradation of IκB (Bai et al. 2009).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1246,883" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="IL6:JAK" from="IL6" to="JAK" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:26297436"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Zebrafish overexpressing human IL6 showed the activation of IL6 receptor gp130 hence JAK phosphorylation (Jung et al. 2015). 
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="RAS:RAF1" from="RAS" to="RAF1" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:11237210"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>GTP-RAS recruits RAF at the membrane and induces the formation of a RAF homo-dimer  thus starting the phosphorylation chain (Avruch et al. 2001)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="RAS:PI3K" from="RAS" to="PI3K" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:9150145"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15677464"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>As reported by (Rodriguez-Viciana et al. 1997) RAS is able in vitro and in intact cells to bind and activate PI3k. (Shin et al. 2005) showed in MCF10A cells,  that H-RAS and N-RAS both activate PI3K pathway.
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1218,581" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="SMAD:SNAIL" from="SMAD" to="SNAIL" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:18832382"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"SMAD and HMGA2 regulate SNAIL expression at the transcriptional level. Furthermore HMGA2 is induced by SMAD (Thuault et al. 2008).
"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="842,990 1616,991" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="WNT:CK1" from="WNT" to="CK1" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:21670201"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:20940130"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(del Valle-Perez, Casagolda, et al. 2011) reports that p120-catenin is phosphorylated on Ser268 and Ser269 by a mechanism depending from CK1ε (David Casagolda et al. 2010) and that  is stimulated by Wnt ligand
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="JAK:STAT3" from="JAK" to="STAT3" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:7612228"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Activated JAK phosphorylates can phosphorylate one or more members of the STAT family (Ihle et al 1995)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="620,789" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="JAK:RAS" from="JAK" to="RAS" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:9126968"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:8995399"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"(Giordano et al. 1997) reported that in  Burkitt's Lymphoma cells overexpressing IL6R and gp130 it is possible to observea tyrosine phosphorylation of p66 Shc after 2 min of IL-6 stimulation, followed by its rapid dephosphorylation at 5 min. This suggests an early signaling pathway of IL-6 mediated by p66 Shc. In vitro evidence of JAK2-Shc complex formation and the consequent complex formation of Grb2/Sos further  support crosstalk between JAK and RAS

(Yin et al. 1997) reported in COS-1 cells that JAK1/2 phosphorylate the SHP-2 phosphatase, the site contains the preferred sequence motif for SH2 binding by Grb2. Moreover in COS-1 cells, co-transfected SHP-2 and JAK2 cDNAs,  endogenous Grb2 proteins could be coprecipitade with SHP-2."
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1000,566" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ERK:GSK3B" from="ERK" to="GSK3B" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:16039586"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Q. Ding et al. 2005) showed, in hepatocellular carcinoma, that  ERK phosphorylates and activates p90RSK, serving also as an adaptor and priming kinase through binding to the DEF domain of GSK3β and phosphorylating GSK3β at the 43T residue, thus facilitating phosphorylation of GSK3β by p90RSK on Ser9, which leads to the inactivation of GSK3β
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1170,844 1170,608" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ERK:SNAIL" from="ERK" to="SNAIL" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:19462441"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Constititively active MEK induce overexpression of SNAIL and SLUG, through ERK activated Fra-1 and Egr-1 (Lemieux et al. 2009), in rat intestinal epithelial crypt cell line IEC-6
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1115,1023" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ERK:SLUG" from="ERK" to="SLUG" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:19462441"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Constititively active MEK induce overexpression of SNAIL and SLUG, through ERK activated Fra-1 and Egr-1 (Lemieux et al. 2009), in rat intestinal epithelial crypt cell line IEC-6
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1277,851" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ERK:FAT4" from="ERK" to="FAT4" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:25679223"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"The transient activation of SRC represses FAT4 mRNA expression in MCF10A cells. SRC activation causes actin depolymerization via MEK/ERK/Cofilin cascade. SRC has been shown to elicit Cofilin-mediated disruption of the actin cytoskeleton through the MEK/ERK pathway. The function of Cofilin is activated via its dephosphorylation.
Treating MCF10A cells or MDA-MB-231 (malignant breast cancer cell), with MEK inhibitor (UO126 or PD0325901) induced FAT4 mRNA upregulation thus pointing to a MEK/ERK dependency (Ito et al. 2015)
"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1045,847 1045,657" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="TGFB:TGFBR" from="TGFB" to="TGFBR" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:1322148"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:8235612"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>TGFβ receptors are serine/threonine kinase receptors (Massagué et al. 1992). The receptor II binds to TGFβ and dimerize with receptor I of which catalize the  phosphorylation (Ebner et al. 1993)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ITG_AB:FAK_SRC" from="ITG_AB" to="FAK_SRC" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:21119598"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>HeyA8  cells plated on fibronectin show FAK activation (p-FAK Y397) and MET activation. This double activation can be reduced by either targeting α5 with an antibody or MET with siRNA. The same cell line HeyA8 were plated on fibronectin and then treated with α5 antibody and different doses of HGF. Resulting in activation of SRC (Tyr416) and an increase in activation of FAK (Mitra et al. 2011).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1490,424" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ITG_AB:FA" from="ITG_AB" to="FA" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <edgevisualsetting points="1337,447 1339,834 1296,834 1298,1302" anchor="NE" style="Modeling activation"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ITG_AB:EGFR" from="ITG_AB" to="EGFR" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:11756413"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Moro et al. 2002) reported how NIH3T3 cells expressing human EGFR and plated on fibronectin showed a coimmunoprecipitation of β1 and EGFR. Furthermore, ECV304 and human primary skin fibroblast adherent on matrix proteins stimulated EGFR phosphorylation and association with the β1 integrin. SRC is phosphorylated on Tyr416 when ECV304 cells are plated on integrin ligands indicating that integrin mediated adhesion induces SRC kinase activation. Under PP1 treatment (a SRC inhibitor) there is no more complex formation between αvβ3 and EGFR similarly if it is expressed a kinase negative form of SRC the complex formation is strongly reduced.
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1224,413 1225,465" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ITG_AB:HGFR" from="ITG_AB" to="HGFR" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:21119598"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Mitra et al. 2011) reported that cMET coimmunoprecipitated with  α5-integrin and confocal microscopy showed a direct interaction. Mice with SKOV3ip1 xenograft showed in vivo that human α5β1-integrin antibody lowered cMET phosphorylation.
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ITG_AB:ILK" from="ITG_AB" to="ILK" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:12642872"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:8538749"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>It is known that ILK binds to β1 and β3  subunits of integrins (G. E. Hannigan et al. 1996). (Cruet-Hennequart et al. 2003) observed the effect of αv-integrin blockade on the ILK activity. 
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1328,671 1297,671" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="BCat:TCF_LEF" from="BCat" to="TCF_LEF" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:23024173"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>TCF_LEF TFs are the end point mediators of Wnt signaling. This family of TFs behaves as repressor as long as there is not signaling to then convert to an activator after its association with β-catenin (Cadigan et al. 2012)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="miR200:ZEB" from="miR200" to="ZEB" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:18829540"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Bracken et al. 2008) there is a double negative feedback loop between miR200 and ZEB
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1602,1198" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="miR200:SLUG" from="miR200" to="SLUG" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:22370643"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Liu et al2013) showed that miR200 can inhibit SLUG. miR-200b directly regulate the stability or translation of SLUG RNA.
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1526,1139 1526,1105 1526,911" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="miR200:ECad" from="miR200" to="ECad" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:﻿25798844"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:﻿18381893"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:21394833"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>According to (Perdigão-Henriques et. al 2016) miR-200 overexpression induced RNA polymerase II localization and reduced Zeb2 and Snail1 complexes binding to epithelial gene promoters in 4TO7 cells. Also ectopic expression of miR200 in cancer cells restore ECadherin expression and slows migration (Park et al. 2008). (Gill et al. 2011) found in ESC that SNAIL drives the EMT and is correlated with the downregulation of miR200, but with a conditional expression of this they were capable of mantaining ECadherin expressed.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1528,1243 1816,1242" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="PAK:SNAIL" from="PAK" to="SNAIL" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15833848"/>
          <link xlink:href=""/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>PAK1 can reuglat nuclear localization of SNAIL by phosphorilating it and decreasing the nuclear export (Yang et al. 2005)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1383,976 1633,978" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="PAK:FA" from="PAK" to="FA" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <edgevisualsetting points="1368,842 1332,843 1331,1318" anchor="NE" style="Modeling activation"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="SNAIL:ECad" from="SNAIL" to="ECad" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:14673164"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>SNAIL is a transcriptional repressor of E-cadherin (Peinado et al 2004).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1852,1034" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="SNAIL:ZEB" from="SNAIL" to="ZEB" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:21317430"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:18347095"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"SNAIL and TWIST1 cooperate to activate the transcrition of ZEB1 in NMuMG (Dave et al. 2011)
SNAIL induces ZEB2 expression vial alternative processing of its mRNA (Beltran et al. 2008)"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1728,1045" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="SNAIL:miR200" from="SNAIL" to="miR200" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:22514743"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:21394833"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"(Moes et al. 2012) showed that miR200b promoter activity was significantly decreased upon SNAIL induction in HEK293T and HCT116 cells.
SNAIL has been shown to repress miR200 in murine embryonic stem cell differentiation (Gill et al. 2011)."
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1646,1155 1544,1156" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="YAP_TAZ:SMAD" from="YAP_TAZ" to="SMAD" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:25937570"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:18568018"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"YAP_TAZ can form complexes with SMAD2/3 thus affecting its capacity to shuttle into the nucleus (Varelas et al 2008 and Grannas 2015)

"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="862,951" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="YAP_TAZ:DVL" from="YAP_TAZ" to="DVL" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:20412773"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Varelas et al. 2010) showed that the  loss of TAZ increases DVL phosphorylation and Wnt-dependent β-catenin activation. Since CK1ε has been reported to phosphorylate DVL cells were treated with an inhibitor of CK1 (IC261) but this resulted only in a partial inhibition of β-catenin stabilization. Thus the  phosphorylated form of YAP_TAZ works as an inhibitor of DVL by sequestering it from CK1ε phosphorylation.
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1006,963 1705,961" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="DELTA:NOTCH" from="DELTA" to="NOTCH" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:2004417"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:11006133"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Lateral inhibition Delta-Notch as in flies  is also present in mammals and represent a non-autonomus short range interaction between adjacent cells expressing the receptor (Heitzler and Simpson 1991). The physical interaction between Delta and Notch has been showed by (Shimizu et al. 2000)
"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="708,345" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="p120_AJ:p120_AJ" from="p120_AJ" to="p120_AJ" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <comment>Modeling interaction, p120 stabilize the E-Cad/B-Cat complex by binding to it. So once the complex is formed we can assume that the removal of the input will not break the complex unless other signal of rupture are sent.
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style="Modeling activation"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="p120_AJ:RAP1" from="p120_AJ" to="RAP1" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:16219685"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Modeling interaction, the progressive strenghtening of cell-cell adhesion that appears on confluent cells is correlated with the inactivation of RAP1
RAP1 is usually induced by unbounded E-Cad or E-Cad/B-Cat complexes that are internalized cause are not stablilized by p120. the downregulation of RAP1 activity is strongly correlated with strenghtening of cadherin adhesions (Balzac et al 2005)"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="2288,790 1508,785" anchor="NE" style="Modelling inhibition"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ROS:JNK" from="ROS" to="JNK" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:18206122"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>ROS oxidizes thioredoxin which dissociate from ASK-1 inducing its activation,  thus resulting in the activation of JNK and p38 pathways (Matsuzawa and Ichijo 2008)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="486,359 486,1236 1399,1233" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ROS:NFkB" from="ROS" to="NFkB" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:27005664"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>In cancer cells and primary cells, the inhibition or deletion of IKK caused, respectively, partial or complete reduction of hypoxia-induced phosphorylation of IκBs on Serine 32 and 36. This translate in an NF-κB activation in a IKK dependent manner (D'Ignazio and Rocha 2016).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="475,1210 1267,1209" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ROS:RPTP" from="ROS" to="RPTP" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:16849327"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15935774"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Y. Xu et al. 2006)  showed how H2O2 addition  to primary keratinocytes induces a reduction in the activity of RPTP-k. In general PTP (internal and receptor like) have been shown to be reversibly-inhibited by ROS like hydrogen peroxide (Denu and Tanner 1998).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="497,328 1887,319" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ROS:FAK_SRC" from="ROS" to="FAK_SRC" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:16024778"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Giannoni et al. 2005) showed how oxidative modification of SRC residues increase its activity in a manner and timing coerent with ROS generation. In particular NIH3T3 cells that  adhere on fibronectin show a first increase in SRC  P-Y416 and a seocnd stronger peak at 45' (in correspondence of a ROS peak).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="507,302 1509,301" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="EGFR:RAS" from="EGFR" to="RAS" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:8019005"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Margolis and Skolnik 1994) reported that after EGF receptor tyrosine kinase activation, docking sites for SH2 form thus initiating multiple signaling cascades. One of which involves the formation of Grb2/Sos complex, which can catalyze Ras GTP/GDP exchange
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="EGFR:JAK" from="EGFR" to="JAK" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15284024"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Primary esophageal keratinocytes activates STAT3 and STAT1 in a JAK dependent way. That can be abolished by the addition of JAK-inhibitor AG-490</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1075,423 636,424" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="EGFR:FAK_SRC" from="EGFR" to="FAK_SRC" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:﻿26079101"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Eberwein et al. 2015) EGFR can activate SRC through the activation of  FAK in ﻿HPV16 E6/E7-immortalized corneal keratinocytes</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1461,500" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="CK1:DVL" from="CK1" to="DVL" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:21606194"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Wnt induces CK1ε activation, which in turn phosphorylates and localize DVL (del Valle-Perez, Arques, et al. 2011).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="CK1:p120_AJ" from="CK1" to="p120_AJ" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:20940130"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>p120 catenin is phosphorylated at Ser268 in response to WNT by CK1ε (D. Casagolda et al. 2010) 
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="BCat_AJ:LATS" from="BCat_AJ" to="LATS" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:21730131"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Depletion of β-catenin in densely cultured MCF10A cells resulted in increased nuclear accumulation of YAP and decreased YAP phosphorylation on the S127 (similar results for A431 and MCF7) (N.-G. Kim et al. 2011)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="2076,647 2001,648 2002,925 1000,927" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="BCat_AJ:BCat" from="BCat_AJ" to="BCat" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <comment>Modeling interaction that account for increased cytoplasm concentration of β-catenin once it is released from the membrane (thus the inhibition sign)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1878,564 1878,613" anchor="NE" style="Modelling inhibition"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="BCat_AJ:ECad_AJ" from="BCat_AJ" to="ECad_AJ" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:10037790"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Modeling interaction, E-cadherin is propely localized at the membrane only if shuttled by β-catenin (Chen et al 1999).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="2102,645" anchor="NE" style="Modeling activation"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ZEB:miR200" from="ZEB" to="miR200" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:18829540"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Bracken et al. 2008) there is a double negative feedback loop between miR200 and ZEB
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1672,1212" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ZEB:ECad" from="ZEB" to="ECad" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15674322"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Eger et al. 2005) ZEB is a transcriptional repressor of E-cadherin
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1867,1203" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ECad_AJ:AJ" from="ECad_AJ" to="AJ" minvalue="2" sign="positive">
      <edgevisualsetting points="2102,1002" anchor="NE" style="Modeling activation"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ECad_AJ:LATS" from="ECad_AJ" to="LATS" minvalue="2" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:21730131"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(N.-G. Kim et al. 2011) showed in MDA-MB-231 cell line that interestingly, doxycycline-induced expression of full-length E-cadherin caused the redistribution of YAP from nucleus to cytoplasm in dense cell cultures,suggesting that E-cadherin is required for the density-dependent regulation of YAP localization
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="2087,934 2086,946 988,938" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ECad_AJ:RAP1" from="ECad_AJ" to="RAP1" minvalue="2" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:16219685"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15254236"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"RAP1 is activated upon Adherens Junction disassembly (C3G and PDZ-GEF bind respectively to E-cadherin and β-catenin) or upon SRC activation.
From the immunoprecipitation of RAP1 it was revealed that RAP1 would be associated with E-cadherin β-catenin a-catenin but not p120Ctn . and that this association increases following the disassenbly of the adherens junction. These levels of assocaition were decreased upon pretreatment with PP2 (SFK inhibitor) (Balzac et al 2005). Furthermore E-cadherin binds C3G (as also SRC) a RAP1 GEF (Hogan et al 2004).

Give these evidences we can formulate RAP1 activation as due to AJ turnover unless there is a stabilization of the same at the membrane (p120)  Or as direct consequence of SRC activation."
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="2076,766 1531,766" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ECad_AJ:p120_AJ" from="ECad_AJ" to="p120_AJ" minvalue="2" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:7876318"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>p120 is associated with E-cadherin using the human carcinoma cell line HT29 (Shibamoto et al. 1995)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="2253,720" anchor="NE" style="Modeling activation"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="ECad_AJ:BCat_AJ" from="ECad_AJ" to="BCat_AJ" effects="1:positive 2:positive">
      <edgevisualsetting points="2095,685 2086,671" anchor="NE" style="Modeling activation"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="RPTP:BCat_AJ" from="RPTP" to="BCat_AJ" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:8663237"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:18276111"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"(Fuchs et al. 1996) shows that RPTP-k colocalize with B-catenin  at cell-cell AJ and that can form a complex with the armadillos proteins.
(Novellino et al. 2008) showed using RPTP-k in different cellular systems, including human melanomas, melanocytes and HEK293 cells, that RPTP-k negatively affected B-catenin transcriptional signaling (stabilization at the membrane)."
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="2091,425" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="RPTP:ECad_AJ" from="RPTP" to="ECad_AJ" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:9531566"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:7642713"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>cadherins and RPTP-mu can form a complex (Brady-Kalnay et al 1998), the inhibition of PTPs activity throguh addition of pervanadate resulted in accumulation of tyrosine phosphorylated cadherins (Brady-Kalnay et al 1995).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1929,696" anchor="NE" style="Modeling activation"/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="RPTP:HGFR" from="RPTP" to="HGFR" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:10425198"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(Hiscox and Jiang 1999) reported that RPTP-mu immunoprecipitated with c-MET in MCF7 and HRT18 cells
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1867,422 1784,405" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="RPTP:EGFR" from="RPTP" to="EGFR" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:16263724"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>RPTP-K can dephopshorlitate EGFR (Xu et al. 2005)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1798,333 1106,334" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="RPTP:JNK" from="RPTP" to="JNK" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:24002526"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>JNK can be inactivated by Ser/Thr and Tyr protein phopshatases. (Sun et al. 2013) showed the regulation of JNK  phosphorilation and activity by RPTP-k  
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1915,1260 1425,1259" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="DVL:GSK3B" from="DVL" to="GSK3B" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:10913153"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>(V. W. Ding, Chen, and McCormick 2000) showed in HEK293 cells a TCF_LEF reporter controlled by DVL/GSK3β combinations
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1637,368" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="DVL:CSL" from="DVL" to="CSL" minvalue="1" sign="negative">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:23132247"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>DVL binds to CSL proteins to reduce their level within the active transcription factor pool (Collu et al. 2012).
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="758,348 759,621 725,622" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="STAT3:SNAIL" from="STAT3" to="SNAIL" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:15129296"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:19724917"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"It represents a multistep interaction STAT3--»LIV1--»SNAIL.
(Yamashita et al. 2004) showed in zebrafish embryo development that LIV1  (downstream target of STAT3) has a crucial role in the EMT of gastrulation  by determining the nuclear localization of SNAIL. Similar results were shown in Panc-1 cells by (Unno et al. 2009).
"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="1564,1045" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="STAT3:HIF1a" from="STAT3" to="HIF1a" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:16007214"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>In MCF7 cells knock down of STAT3 abrogate HIF1-α expression (Q. Xu et al. 2005) 
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="762,1072" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="CSL:SNAIL" from="CSL" to="SNAIL" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:18427106"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>NICD or CSL can induce SNAIL transcription (Sahlgren et al 2008)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="841,1009" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="CSL:SLUG" from="CSL" to="SLUG" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:18663143"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:17984306"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>"Slug is a direct Notch target in endothelial cells (Niessen et al 2008)
Notch activation induces Slug mediated repression of E-cadherin (Leong et al. 2007)

"
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="758,927 758,874" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="CSL:NFkB" from="CSL" to="NFkB" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:25048699"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:﻿12107827"/>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:﻿18059366"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Notch intracellular domain increases NF-κB activity (Kwon et al. 2014). (Nickoloff et al. 2002) human keratinocytes Jag-1 induces NF-kB activity.
Cross talk between Notch and NF-κB (Osipo et al. 2008)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <edgevisualsetting points="708,1163" anchor="NE" style=""/>
    </edge>
    <edge id="FAT4_L:FAT4" from="FAT4_L" to="FAT4" minvalue="1" sign="positive">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="pmid:17045801"/>
